       you can use [1mmake[0m with any programming language whose compiler can be run with a shell command.  In fact, [1mmake[0m is not lim‐[m
       ited  to  programs.  You can use it to describe any task where some files must be updated automatically from others when‐[m
       ever the others change.[m
[m
       To prepare to use [1mmake[0m, you must write a file called the [4mmakefile[24m that describes the relationships among  files  in  your[m
       program, and the states the commands for updating each file.  In a program, typically the executable file is updated from[m
       object files, which are in turn made by compiling source files.[m
[m
       Once a suitable makefile exists, each time you change some source files, this simple shell command:[m
[m
              [1mmake[0m[m
[m
       suffices to perform all necessary recompilations.  The [1mmake[0m program uses the makefile description and the  last-modifica‐[m
       tion times of the files to decide which of the files need to be updated.  For each of those files, it issues the commands[m
       recorded in the makefile.[m
[m
       [1mmake[0m executes commands in the [4mmakefile[24m to update one or more target [4mnames[24m, where [4mname[24m is typically a program.  If  no  [1m-f[0m[m
       option is present, [1mmake[0m will look for the makefiles [4mGNUmakefile[24m, [4mmakefile[24m, and [4mMakefile[24m, in that order.[m
[m
